# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# codex-remote-railway — app service variables
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Copy the values you need into the Railway service "Variables" tab (NOT into
# a committed .env file). The IaC (.railway/railway.ts) sets the non-secret
# defaults for you; the entries below marked as SECRET must be set manually
# because IaC intentionally does not embed secret material.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

# --- Start mode -------------------------------------------------------------
# What the container should run:
#   tailscale-only   (DEFAULT) — bring the container onto the tailnet and
#                    keep it alive. No Codex is started. Use this to SSH in
#                    over the tailnet and set up Codex interactively (or
#                    when you just want a remote-env sandbox).
#   codex+tailscale  — tailscaled + `codex app-server` with capability-token
#                    WebSocket auth on ${PORT}. Requires CODEX_WS_TOKEN.
# START_MODE=tailscale-only

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Tailscale (REQUIRED for the initial bring-up)
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# On FIRST boot with an empty volume, TS_AUTHKEY must be set — the entrypoint
# uses it once to join the tailnet. The node identity is then persisted at
# /var/lib/tailscale (which is on the /workspace volume via a symlink), so on
# every subsequent redeploy the container reuses that identity and does NOT
# call `tailscale up` again. That means:
#   • same tailnet DNS name across redeploys
#   • same tailnet IP across redeploys
#   • no repeated joins/registrations in the Tailscale admin console
#   • TS_AUTHKEY can be revoked after the first successful join
#
# Generate a REUSABLE auth key at
#   https://login.tailscale.com/admin/settings/keys
# TS_AUTHKEY and TAILSCALE_AUTHKEY are accepted interchangeably.
TS_AUTHKEY=tskey-auth-REPLACE_ME_ON_FIRST_BOOT_ONLY

# Tailnet node name. Kept stable across redeploys because it's part of the
# persisted identity, so only the very first boot uses this value to name
# the node.
TS_HOSTNAME=codex-remote-railway

# Optional extra `tailscale up` arguments (word-split). Example:
# TS_EXTRA_ARGS=--advertise-tags=tag:codex-remote --accept-routes

# Override the tailscaled state directory. Default is /var/lib/tailscale
# which is symlinked into /workspace/.tailscale-state by the entrypoint.
# TS_STATE_DIR=/var/lib/tailscale

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Codex app-server (ONLY used when START_MODE=codex+tailscale)
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Railway injects PORT at runtime; the entrypoint binds the app-server to it.
# CODEX_LISTEN_HOST rarely needs changing. Default 0.0.0.0 so both the Railway
# public domain and the Tailscale interface can reach the app-server.
# CODEX_LISTEN_HOST=0.0.0.0

# Capability-token auth. Either set the plaintext token (recommended — the
# entrypoint derives the SHA-256 digest at boot and unsets the plaintext
# before exec) OR pre-compute the digest yourself and set CODEX_WS_TOKEN_SHA256.
#
# Generate a strong token locally:
#   openssl rand -base64 48 | tr -d '=+/' | cut -c1-64
#
# Then paste the SAME value into the local shell that runs the client:
#   export CODEX_WS_TOKEN='paste-the-same-value-here'
#   codex --remote wss://<host>:<port> --remote-auth-token-env CODEX_WS_TOKEN
# CODEX_WS_TOKEN=REPLACE_WITH_STRONG_RANDOM_TOKEN

# Alternative — pre-computed SHA-256 hex digest, no plaintext on the server:
#   printf %s "$CODEX_WS_TOKEN" | sha256sum
# CODEX_WS_TOKEN_SHA256=REPLACE_WITH_HEX_SHA256_DIGEST

# Model auth (one of the two, only used in codex+tailscale mode):
#   Option A — API key (simplest):
# OPENAI_API_KEY=sk-REPLACE_ME
#
#   Option B — ChatGPT / Codex sign-in:
# Run `codex login` on any machine, then copy the resulting ~/.codex/auth.json
# into the Railway volume at /root/.codex/auth.json.

# Optional Codex tuning:
# CODEX_HOME=/root/.codex
# CODEX_LOG_LEVEL=info
